&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Kent Beck wrote:
&gt;  &gt; &gt; David,
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; I think that the framework should continue to work in as
&gt;  &gt; many situations as
&gt;  &gt; &gt; possible. If a listener throws an exception, the framework
&gt;  &gt; should deal with
&gt;  &gt; &gt; it. Contributing to Eclipse calls this the Safe Platform
&gt;  &gt; Rule: &quot;As the
&gt;  &gt; &gt; provider of an extension point, you must protect yourself against
&gt;  &gt; &gt; misbehavior on the part of extenders.&quot; Here is the test I
&gt;  &gt; came up with that
&gt;  &gt; &gt; I think should pass (and doesn&#39;t currently):
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;       int count;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;     
&gt;  &gt; &gt;       class FailingListener implements TestListener {
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             public void testRunStarted(int testCount) {
&gt;  &gt; &gt;                   count++;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;                   throw new Error();
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             }
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             public void testRunFinished(Runner runner) {
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             }
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             public void testStarted(Object test, String name) {
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             }
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             public void testFinished(Object test, String name) {
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             }
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             public void testFailure(Failure failure) {
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             }
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             public void testIgnored(Method method) {
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             }
&gt;  &gt; &gt;       }
&gt;  &gt; &gt;     
&gt;  &gt; &gt;       public static class OneTest {
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             @Test public void nothing() {}
&gt;  &gt; &gt;       }
&gt;  &gt; &gt;     
&gt;  &gt; &gt;       @Test public void failingListener() {
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             count= 0;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             Runner runner= new Runner();
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             runner.addListener(new FailingListener());
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             runner.addListener(new FailingListener());
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             runner.run(OneTest.class);
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             assertEquals(2, count);
&gt;  &gt; &gt;       }
&gt;  &gt; &gt;     
&gt;  &gt; &gt;     
&gt;  &gt; &gt;       public static junit.framework.Test suite() {
&gt;  &gt; &gt;             return new JUnit4TestAdapter(TestListenerTest.class);
&gt;  &gt; &gt;       }
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; I am working on an implementation. Alternatively, should
&gt;  &gt; the count be 1?
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; If you&#39;re wondering whether the new FailingListeners should
&gt;  &gt; be counted
&gt;  &gt; as equal, I believe not. They aren&#39;t Value Objects, so I don&#39;t think
&gt;  &gt; they should be compared with value equality.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; If you&#39;re wondering about something else, then ignore me and
&gt;  &gt; wait for an
&gt;  &gt; intelligent reply.
&gt; 
&gt; J.B.
&gt; 
&gt; The equality of the listeners wasn&#39;t in question. I wrote the test the way I
&gt; did so that it didn&#39;t matter what order the listeners were called (it isn&#39;t
&gt; guaranteed), the test would prove that both listeners were called in spite
&gt; of their exceptions. My first version of the test had one failing listener
&gt; and a second listener that set a flag that was checked with assertTrue(),
&gt; but that test implicitly relied on the listeners being called in the order
&gt; they were added.

